column23:
The survey focuses on environmental issues, with a particular focus on air pollution. It should take approximately 15-20 minutes to complete. The interviews are coordinated by researchers from the ETH Zurich in Switzerland. The research is financed by the Swiss Network for International Studies and the Swiss National Science Foundation.  This research is intended solely for scientific purposes.



In this survey we would like to ask some questions that may be perceived as sensitive such as your political opinion. Providing information in response to these questions is entirely voluntary, and you may withdraw your consent at any time.



The information collected in this interview will be stored and analysed in a confidential manner that does not allow for any conclusions about individual participants. There are no known risks of participating in this interview. The interview content has been reviewed and approved by the ETH Zurich Ethics Committee (24_ETHICS-388).



To obtain scientifically useful findings, we rely on your participation and greatly appreciate your time and input. Please read/listen to each question carefully and answer to the best of your knowledge.

column483: This is a very fascinating study, particularly since the has been a drastic increase in anthropogenic activities which has increased the concentration of greenhouse gases which has also led to intensified greenhouse effect. More efforts should be taken to address the biggest culprit to poor ambient Air quality especially within the townshipswhich is burning of biomass. Another issue in Soweto particularly the areas in the vicinity of mine tailings or residues, there is always an increase level of particulate matter in windy seasons and this has significant detrimental impacts on vulnerable groups such as children,older people a d immunocompromissed Individuals.  Yes I've heard that there  are measures taken to reduce dust emanating from these mine dumps but I really feel the rehabilitation is not enough. There must be regular checks of wind rows in these mine dumps. As an aspiring air quality officer I really support such  initiatives to help prevent, control and mitigate activities that results to poor ambient Air quality.
